{{Infobox monarch | name = Ali ibn Faramurz | title = [[Emir]] of [[Yazd]] and [[Abarkuh]] | image = | caption = | reign = Ca. 1070&nbsp;– 1095 | predecessor = [[Faramurz]] | successor = [[Garshasp II]] | queen = Arslan Khatun | royal house = [[Kakuyids|Kakuyid]] | father = [[Faramurz]] | birth_date = Unknown | birth_place = [[Iran]] | death_date = 1095 | death_place = [[Ray, Iran|Ray]] | religion = [[Islam]] }} '''Ali ibn Faramurz''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]: علی بن فرامرز), was the [[Kakuyid]] [[Emir]] of [[Yazd]] and [[Abarkuh]]. He was the son of [[Faramurz]].
== Biography ==
In 1076/1077, Ali married a daughter of [[Chaghri Beg]] named Arslan Katun, who was the widow of the [[Abbasid]] [[Caliph]] [[Al-Qa'im (caliph)|Al-Qa'im]] (1031-1075). Ali was a faithful vassal Seljuk and spent most of his reign at the court of the Seljuq [[Malik-Shah I]] in [[Isfahan]]. He was a patron of the [[Persian people|Persian]] poet [[Mu'izzi]] who made some poems dedicated to him.{{sfn|Bosworth|1985|pp=848–849}}
After the death of Malik-Shah I in 1092, Ali supported his brother [[Tutush I]] that dominated the western part of the [[Seljuq Empire]], and considered his right to the throne more superior than [[Barkiyaruq]]. Tutush, however, was decisively defeated in a battle near [[Ray, Iran|Ray]] in 1095, where he and Ali were killed.{{sfn|Bosworth|1985|pp=848–849}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=38}} Ali was succeeded by his son [[Garshasp II]].
