{{MedalTop}} {{MedalSport|Men's [[Rowing at the Summer Olympics|rowing]]}} {{MedalSilver|[[1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Paris]] | [[Rowing at the 1924 Summer Olympics – Men's eight|Eight]]}} {{MedalBottom}}
Dr. '''Warren Bertram Snyder''' (March 2, 1903 in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]] &ndash; March 27, 1957) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] athlete and doctor. Snyder competed for Canada in [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]] in the [[1924 Summer Olympics]]. Snyder won the silver medal as crew member of the Canadian boat in the eights event. Before he competed in the men’s eights at the 1924 Summer Olympics, Snyder was well known as a basketball, baseball, and rugby football player. As a 17-year old, he helped the [[Toronto Varsity Blues football|University of Toronto Varsity Blues]] defeat the [[Toronto Argonauts]] 16-3 to win the Grey Cup in [[8th Grey Cup|1920]]. At the 1924 Olympics, his Varsity Blues eights squad, which consisted of [[Arthur Bell (rower)|Arthur Bell]], [[Ivor Campbell]], [[Robert Hunter (rower)|Robert Hunter]], [[William Langford (rower)|William Langford]], [[Harold Little]], [[John Smith (Canadian rower)|John Smith]], [[Norman Taylor]], and [[William Wallace (rower)|William Wallace]], lost their heat to the United States, but earned the right to compete in the final by winning the repêchage. There they were again defeated by the United States, but captured the silver medal ahead of the Italians and the Britons.
